collections.name: humann
collections.description:
A deep crack opened in the body of time, pulling humanity inside. Yesterday, it walked upon stones sealed with blood. Its eyes watched shadows grow in the flickering light of fire. When the blade met the bone, justice was born; hunger tamed instinct. Hands were stained with soil and bloo
Then came the age of metal, followed by the age of silicon. Eyes no longer reflected the flames but the cold glow of blue screens. Voices turned into vibrations; fingertips caressed codes instead of letters. As humanity forgot itself, it transformed.

Today, we stand at the sharpest edge of time. Thoughts are no longer thought; desires are designed. Bodies are forgotten inside metal shells, souls stored in databases. Man first created gods, then abandoned itself to become one.

And tomorrow, as the last echo of humanity fades into the digital void, perhaps a voice will rise to remember the real question:
“Who forgot me?

collections.name: MIXED METHODS
collections.description:
My vision:

... creatively rethinking societal theory!

As a scholar of the sociology of religion and a passionate artist, I find endless inspiration in societal theories. 

In my work and collection I explore contemporary issues and late-modern theories through an artistic lens, creatively interpreting sociological concepts.

Thematically, I focus on how western society deals with individualization, digitalization or artificial intelligence, the relationship between humans and nature in the 21st century, and the challenges of constant change and how we navigate them in our daily lives.

My collection title [MIXED-METHODS] is inspired by my daily and favorite methodological approach called “Mixed-Methods” , which combines qualitative and quantitative analyzing methods in studies to get the most representative result.
